      "content": "The marginal tax rates people face when they start earning money are a legitimate concern, but they're often overstated and used to justify draconian cuts to social safety nets. The idea that people are deterred from working by the prospect of losing benefits is a classic example of the \"Laffer Curve\" fallacy, which assumes that higher taxes will lead to higher economic growth, but ignores the complexities of the real world. In reality, the marginal tax rates people face are often much lower than the rates that would be imposed by a hypothetical \"welfare trap,\" and the benefits of increased labor force participation far outweigh the costs of any marginal tax increases.",
